    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The danger of moist and wet avalanches will increase during the day.</highlights>
      <comment>The conditions are generally favourable for ski touring. The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust and will soften during the day. &lt;br/> Locally, the night may be cloudy; in that case, the avalanche danger will already be 2—moderate by morning because The surface of the snowpack will only just freeze and will already be soft in the early morning. And so conditions in the mid-mountain range will already be somewhat unfavourable. &lt;br/> In the late morning the natural activity of moist and wet avalanches will gradually increase. At low and intermediate altitudes and on very steep slopes small and medium-sized moist snow slides and avalanches are to be expected. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> As a consequence of new snow and a sometimes moderate southeasterly wind, sometimes avalanche prone wind slabs formed. They have formed at high altitudes and in high Alpine regions.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>Colder than expected: The surface of the snowpack has frozen to form a strong crust. 20 to 40 cm of snow, and even more in some localities, has fallen since Sunday above approximately 2300 m. New snow and wind slabs are lying on a wet old snowpack. &lt;br/> At higher altitudes, snow cover becomes thinner and patchy; it is better at mid-altitudes, which are less exposed to the wind. Below approximately 1900 m hardly any snow is lying. &lt;br/> Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
      <highlights>As a consequence of warming during the day and solar radiation more moist and wet avalanches are possible. Sunshine and high temperatures will give rise to settling of the snowpack. Backcountry tours and ascents to alpine cabins should be concluded timely.</highlights>
      <tendencyType>decreasing</tendencyType>
